export const murals = [
  {id:1,a:'Aaron Tullo',t:'',loc:'253 2nd Ave N',bldg:'Cordova Inn',lat:27.773992,lng:-82.636422,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'aaron.tullo',bio:'Aaron Tullo is a St. Petersburg-based muralist, sign painter, and fine artist who operates under the Aaron James Tullo Fine Art studio. His work blends figurative realism with bold graphic design, drawing on his background in both traditional painting and commercial art — including work for clients such as St. Pete College, Penn Fishing Reels, and Old Northeast Jewelers. A former minor league baseball player, Tullo channels his travels and community connections into story-driven public art that celebrates place and people. He participated in the 2025 SHINE Origins festival, painting a five-story mural on the Cordova Inn, the festival\'s title sponsor.',desc:'This five-story mural on the facade of the Cordova Inn depicts a large white peacock rendered in Tullo\'s characteristic blend of figurative realism and bold graphic composition. The bird\'s plumage fills the building\'s vertical expanse, creating a striking visual landmark in downtown St. Petersburg.',img:'images/murals/2025/aaron-tullo.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:2,a:'Amy Ilic-Volpe',t:'Here & Now',loc:'31st St & 7th Ave S',bldg:'',lat:27.762931,lng:-82.674592,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'amy_ilic_volpe',bio:'Amy Ilic-Volpe is a St. Petersburg-based multimedia artist whose work explores the interplay of color, form, and perception. Her bold, graphic style uses bright palettes and layered geometric compositions to create work that feels both playful and contemplative. She was the 2022 Gasparilla Festival of the Arts Emerging Artist Recipient, a featured artist in All She Makes magazine, and a SHINE St. Petersburg "Bright Spot" artist in 2022. For the 2025 SHINE Origins festival she returned with a full-scale mural on 31st St & 7th Ave S.',desc:'A wide, vibrant mural on a cinder block wall bursting with overlapping geometric shapes — circles, stripes, polka dots, and waves — in a candy- bright palette of pink, green, yellow, orange, purple, and turquoise. The left side features the words "Here & Now" in stacked multicolor block letters. Signed "Amy Ilic Volpe @amy_ilic_volpe" in pink in the lower right corner.',img:'images/murals/2025/amy-ilic-volpe.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:3,a:'Brain The Genius',t:'Culture',loc:'31st St & 7th Ave S',bldg:'',lat:27.762931,lng:-82.674592,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'brainthegenius',bio:'Chris Roberts, known as BRAIN The Genius (formerly Brain Storm), is a St. Petersburg multidisciplinary artist, tattoo artist, and entrepreneur. He has spent over two decades building Urban Ink Tattoo Company into one of the city\'s most respected studios, recognized as one of the rare Black-owned businesses in the body art community. Beyond tattooing, he is an accomplished painter, designer, and cinematographer who founded Culture Creative, a dynamic art and event space on 34th Street South that amplifies local talent. He painted a SHINE Bright Spot mural in 2020 at the St. Pete Youth Farm and returned for the 2025 SHINE Origins festival.',desc:'A bold mural on a cinder block wall featuring the word "Culture" in ornate gold script, framed by oversized gold bamboo hoop earrings and topped with a gold crown. Lush monstera leaves fill the background in deep greens against black. The left side reads "Bamboo Earrings At Least Two Pair" in white graffiti-style lettering — a nod to the LL Cool J lyric. Signed "BRAIN @brainthegenius" in the lower right.',img:'images/murals/2025/brain-the-genius.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:4,a:'Cecilia Lueza',t:'',loc:'251 10th St N',bldg:'Haddy',lat:27.774508,lng:-82.647736,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'cecilialuezaap',bio:'Cecilia Lueza is an Argentine American artist and sculptor who studied fine arts at the University of La Plata in Buenos Aires. After moving to St. Petersburg over two decades ago, she became known for vibrant public art spanning murals, monumental sculptures, painted rooftops, and even street intersections. Her geometric, nature-inspired style has been shown in galleries throughout the US, South America, Spain, and France. A SHINE veteran, Lueza painted "Common Ground" — an entire intersection — for SHINE 2016, "The Blue Hour" for SHINE 2018, and returned again for SHINE 2019 and 2025 Origins.',desc:'A large-scale mural on the side of a commercial building depicting a vividly colored hummingbird in flight, wings spread wide, rendered in iridescent greens, blues, and oranges. The bird hovers against a dynamic background of overlapping translucent circles in gradients of blue, teal, green, and yellow — Lueza\'s signature geometric style. Signed "LUEZA" in the upper right. The building number 255 is visible at the left edge.',img:'images/murals/2025/cecilia-lueza.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:5,a:'Derek Donnelly',t:'',loc:'1847 1st Ave N',bldg:'',lat:27.7724559,lng:-82.658692,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'saintpaintarts',bio:'Derek Donnelly, known as Saint Paint Arts, is a St. Petersburg native whose cartoon-influenced murals have become landmarks across Tampa Bay. A multiple Best of the Bay winner from Creative Loafing Tampa Bay, Donnelly\'s playful, story-driven style blends retro illustration with local culture — often featuring his son and the city\'s wildlife. His large-scale work spans hotels, breweries, public buildings, and private homes throughout the region. For the 2025 SHINE Origins festival, he painted two murals: this piece at 1847 1st Ave N and a vintage postcard companion at the Hollander Hotel.',desc:'A wide-format mural wrapping around two walls of a single-story building. The central scene shows Donnelly\'s signature cartoon boy — in a red cap and sunglasses — riding a pelican in flight over ocean waves. A dragonfly hovers on the right side, and seagulls fill the sky. The left wall transitions into an underwater scene in deep blue-green tones, with a diver amid coral and sea life. Signed "Donnelly" in the upper right. The palette shifts from cool oceanic blues on the left to bright sky blue and green on the right.',img:'images/murals/2025/derek-donnelly-1847.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:6,a:'Derek Donnelly',t:'Greetings from Hollander Hotel',loc:'421 4th Ave N',bldg:'Hollander Hotel',lat:27.776731,lng:-82.638764,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'saintpaintarts',bio:'Derek Donnelly, known as Saint Paint Arts, is a St. Petersburg native whose cartoon-influenced murals have become landmarks across Tampa Bay. A multiple Best of the Bay winner from Creative Loafing Tampa Bay, Donnelly\'s playful, story-driven style blends retro illustration with local culture — often featuring his son and the city\'s wildlife. His large-scale work spans hotels, breweries, public buildings, and private homes throughout the region. For the 2025 SHINE Origins festival, he painted two murals: this vintage postcard piece at the Hollander Hotel and a companion work at 1847 1st Ave N.',desc:'A vintage-style postcard mural reading "Greetings from Hollander Hotel, St. Pete, FL." A cartoon boy in a red cap rides a pelican wearing sunglasses over turquoise waters, with dolphins leaping below, seagulls overhead, and a palm-tree island with the Sunshine Skyway Bridge in the distance. Signed "Donnelly @Saint Paint Arts" in the lower right. The retro color palette of teals, creams, and warm tans gives it a classic Florida tourism feel.',img:'images/murals/2025/derek-donnelly-hollander.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:7,a:'Dreamweaver',t:'',loc:'696 1st Ave N',bldg:'Vernis Bowling',lat:27.771708,lng:-82.643617,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'dream.weavin',bio:'Taylor "Dreamweaver" Smith is a St. Petersburg-based street artist and muralist whose work invokes a sense of reverence for the natural world. With a background in fine art, her evolving style integrates expressive abstraction and realism to capture the spirit of life through light and color — often featuring portraiture, vivid patterns, and striking color combinations. She creates murals, canvas works, and live painting activations for communities and brands both locally and nationwide. A recurring SHINE artist, Dreamweaver painted at the 2022 festival and returned for 2025 Origins on the 600 block of Central Avenue, where the SHINE movement started in 2012.',desc:'A multi-story mural wrapping around a lavender building, featuring a white egret with delicate plumage nestled among enormous, lush flower petals in deep pinks, corals, oranges, and purples. The bird\'s long neck rises elegantly through the blooms on the left wall, while the right wall continues with swirling petals and soft round forms in warm sunset tones. The scale is dramatic — the egret spans several stories — and the soft-focus, almost photorealistic rendering gives the whole piece a dreamlike, ethereal quality.',img:'images/murals/2025/dreamweaver.jpeg',from:'Tampa, FL'},
  {id:8,a:'Elizabeth Barenis',t:'',loc:'31st St & 7th Ave S',bldg:'',lat:27.762931,lng:-82.674592,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'elizabethbarenis',bio:'Born and raised in Greenville, Mississippi, Elizabeth Barenis has been painting since childhood. A graduate of Sarah Lawrence College in New York, she was named a 2023 Creative Pinellas Professional Artist grantee and participated in the 2018 International Painting Symposium at the Mark Rothko Art Center in Latvia. Her signature "Abstract Precisionism" style, inspired by her photography, uses softly abstracted shapes and colors to evoke tranquility and beauty. Now based in Pinellas County, she believes "it\'s the artist\'s job to amplify" beauty and that "art for a community really uplifts the community." She participated in the 2025 SHINE Origins festival.',desc:'A wide mural on a cinder block wall depicting oversized tropical fan palm fronds in layered shades of green, teal, and soft yellow. The leaves radiate outward in clean, geometric planes — Barenis\'s "Abstract Precisionism" style — creating depth through overlapping translucent shapes. Signed "Elizabeth Barenis 2025" in the lower left corner.',img:'images/murals/2025/elizabeth-barenis.jpeg',from:'Pinellas County, FL'},
  {id:118,a:'Elizabeth Barenis',t:'Healing Palms',loc:'744 6th Ave. S.',bldg:'Bayfront Health St. Pete',lat:27.764375,lng:-82.64328,y:2025,cat:'commercial',ig:'',bio:'Elizabeth Barenis is a St. Petersburg-based painter originally from Greenville, Mississippi, who studied at Sarah Lawrence College in New York. She works in a style she calls "Abstract Precisionism" — gently abstracted shapes and colors drawn from her photography, intended to recreate moments of tranquility. She was named a 2023 Creative Pinellas Professional Artist grantee and participated in the International Painting Symposium at the Mark Rothko Art Center in Latvia in 2018. "Healing Palms" was commissioned by Orlando Health as an original painting, then enlarged and printed on the louvered exterior wall of the Bayfront Hospital ambulance entrance. The installation translates her tropical foliage compositions to architectural scale, wrapping the building in overlapping palm fronds rendered in cool greens and blues.',desc:'Overlapping angular planes in shades of green and blue fill the louvered exterior wall of the Bayfront Health ambulance entrance. The geometric shapes suggest tropical palm fronds abstracted into faceted, crystalline forms — a diptych painting enlarged to building scale. The cool palette and precise geometry complement the medical campus architecture while adding a distinctly tropical warmth.',img:'images/murals/commercial/unknown-1498.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:9,a:'Isac Gres',t:'',loc:'699 Central Ave',bldg:'Melting Pot',lat:27.771678,lng:-82.643892,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'isacgres.art',bio:'Isac Gres (b. 1993, Cuba) is a surrealist painter, muralist, and tattoo artist whose work transforms themes of exile, memory, and resilience into dreamlike imagery. After a 12-country journey to the U.S., he developed a symbolic language of doorways, jellyfish, and apples — metaphors of identity and transformation. His large-scale work blends hyperrealistic technique with cosmic surrealism, often featuring a recurring motif of beaming light that he describes as representing "light and good energy." For the 2025 SHINE Origins festival, Gres took on his tallest wall to date on the 600 block of Central Avenue — where the mural movement that launched SHINE began in 2012 — alongside Dreamweaver and John Vitale.',desc:'A massive two-story mural wrapping around the corner of a building in swirling cosmic surrealism. The composition features molten planetary spheres, a city skyline encased in a dripping glass orb, melting candles nodding to Dalí, and a sculptural elephant form emerging from fiery nebula clouds. The palette is dominated by deep space blues and purples contrasted with blazing oranges, reds, and golds. Signed "Isac Gres" in the lower corners of both walls.',img:'images/murals/2025/isac-gres.jpeg',from:'Cuba / St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:10,a:'Jenipher Chandley',t:'Stronger Together',loc:'31st St & 7th Ave S',bldg:'',lat:27.762867,lng:-82.675103,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'jenipherchandley',bio:'Jenipher Chandley is a St. Petersburg-based representational artist whose work explores the relationship between nature and the human condition, focusing on themes of strength, beauty, loss, and resilience. Working predominantly with oils, she creates figurative artwork infused with surrealism and symbolism. She holds degrees in Interior and Graphic Design and has shown her work in hundreds of shows and charitable events while curating exhibitions throughout Tampa Bay. A 2023 Creative Pinellas Emerging Artist grantee, she has also been selected as the Local Artist Spotlight by the Gasparilla Festival of the Arts and featured by American Stage Theater. She participated in SHINE 2021 and returned for SHINE Origins 2025.',desc:'A wide mural on a cinder block wall with the words "Stronger Together" in large flowing white script across a deep teal background. The text is framed by a lush border of curling green vines and tropical flame-colored flowers — gloriosa lilies in reds, oranges, and yellows. Signed "Jenipher Chandley" in the upper right corner.',img:'images/murals/2025/jenipher-chandley.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:11,a:'John Vitale',t:'Power to the Patients',loc:'600 1st Ave N',bldg:'',lat:27.7716472,lng:-82.6446195,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'vitalebros',bio:'John Vitale, co-founder of the iconic Vitale Brothers, is a veteran muralist and creative force behind much of St. Petersburg\'s visual identity. Since 1992, the Vitale Bros have painted walls throughout Tampa Bay, playing a major role in establishing St. Petersburg as a world-class arts destination. John is also the founder of Overspray Art Space in Gulfport, where he fosters community through spray paint workshops and live art events. With over three decades of experience painting large-scale public works, he combines classic craftsmanship with bold, contemporary design. A recurring SHINE artist, he painted at SHINE 2022 and returned for SHINE Origins 2025 on the 600 block where the mural movement began.',desc:'A propaganda-style mural in the tradition of Shepard Fairey\'s OBEY aesthetic. A raised fist gripping a caduceus medical symbol is centered in a bold red circle, with "Power to the Patients" in block letters below. The top reads "Prices Are Now a Patient\'s Right" and the bottom banner declares "Demand Them!!!" in large cream type on red. The palette is limited to navy blue, red, cream, and gray — evoking classic activist poster art. "PowerToThePatients.org" runs along the bottom, with Vitale Bros logos flanking it.',img:'images/murals/2025/john-vitale-600.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:12,a:'John Vitale & Sionna MacLeish',t:'',loc:'2606 Fairfield Ave S',bldg:'The Factory',lat:27.763314,lng:-82.668853,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'vitalebros',bio:'John Vitale, co-founder of the iconic Vitale Brothers, is a veteran muralist and creative force behind much of St. Petersburg\'s visual identity. Since 1992, the Vitale Bros have painted walls throughout Tampa Bay, playing a major role in establishing St. Petersburg as a world-class arts destination. John is also the founder of Overspray Art Space in Gulfport, where he fosters community through spray paint workshops and live art events. For this mural at The Factory, Vitale collaborated with Sionna "Sio" MacLeish, a Florida-based muralist and artist known for her versatility across styles. MacLeish painted the roseate spoonbill panel, while Vitale handled the vintage pin-up and Thunderbird motel scene.',desc:'A multi-panel vintage Florida postcard mural inside The Factory. The left panel features a glamorous 1950s-style pin-up woman with black hair and a pink hibiscus, turquoise jewelry, and a leopard-print top, set against the Thunderbird motel sign framed by tropical hibiscus flowers. Below reads "St. Petersburg, Florida" in retro blue script on golden yellow. The right panel, painted by Sionna MacLeish, shows a roseate spoonbill in soft pinks against a pale blue polka-dot background with a bold orange sun. The whole composition evokes mid-century Florida tourism nostalgia.',img:'images/murals/2025/john-vitale-factory.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:13,a:'Karel Garcia',t:'',loc:'31st St & 7th Ave S',bldg:'',lat:27.762931,lng:-82.674478,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'karelgarcia.fineartist',bio:'Karel Garcia (b. 1990, Vedado, Cuba) trained as an architect in Havana, completing his degree in 2017. While working as an architect, he reconnected with art through exhibitions including projects at the Habana Espacio Creativo Center, developing his "Human" series exploring the human experience. After emigrating to Florida, he joined the Green Book of Tampa Bay residency program with a studio in St. Petersburg\'s Warehouse Arts District. The 2025 SHINE Origins festival marked Garcia\'s first public art installation in America. "My mural is about my history, coming here to America, looking for freedom. So it\'s about migration, love, freedom, family, and live your truth," he said.',desc:'A wide mural on a cinder block wall depicting bold, swirling ocean waves in deep blues and greens against a golden-orange sky. Three carved wooden totem-like hands rise from the waves, and small red paper boats ride the cresting swells — symbols of migration and hope. The flowing, graphic linework gives the waves a stylized, rhythmic energy. Signed "Karel Garcia" in the lower right.',img:'images/murals/2025/karel-garcia.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:15,a:'Rebekah Lazaridis',t:'',loc:'31st St & 7th Ave S',bldg:'',lat:27.762931,lng:-82.674544,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'rebekahlaz',bio:'Rebekah Eugenia Lazaridis is a St. Pete native and multidisciplinary artist who graduated with a BFA from The School of the Art Institute of Chicago in 2005. A scenic artist and designer, she has created sets for productions at American Stage, Jobsite, freeFall, and Stageworks. She also runs @homeillustrations, creating customized home portraits with a nostalgic flair, and her CIRCA series portrays iconic St. Petersburg spots in a vintage postcard style. Her first NYC solo show explored theatrical superstitions. She participated in SHINE 2025 Origins at 31st St & 7th Ave S.',desc:'A dramatic monochromatic mural on a black cinder block wall. A large ornate Gothic letter "B" with intricate Celtic knotwork fills the center, overlaid on a detailed full moon rendered in grays and whites. Bats swarm from the left across the night sky, and a barn owl with outstretched wings emerges from storm clouds on the right, with rain streaking diagonally downward. Signed "ReAh @rebekahlaz" in the lower right corner. The entire palette is black, white, and silver — a stark contrast to the colorful murals flanking it.',img:'images/murals/2025/rebekah-lazaridis.jpeg',from:'Pinellas County, FL'},
  {id:16,a:'Reid Jenkins',t:'',loc:'2039 1st Ave S',bldg:'Founders Pro',lat:27.770058,lng:-82.661369,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'nighttakesking',bio:'Reid Jenkins is a St. Petersburg native who holds a BFA from Maryland Institute College of Art and is a graduate of the P.C.C.A program at Gibbs High School. His work spans murals, canvas paintings, and tattoos — he currently tattoos at Fabled Trade Tattoo Company in Lealman and maintains a studio at the Arts Exchange in the Warehouse Arts District. Jenkins aims to paint the human experience and capture the small moments that many forget to appreciate. He painted a SHINE mural in 2021 and returned for SHINE Origins 2025 with this botanical piece at Founders Pro.',desc:'A stunning photorealistic botanical mural on the side of a commercial building against a deep black background. An overflowing arrangement of tropical flowers fills the wall — king proteas, red ginger, heliconia, pincushion proteas, orchids, and ferns rendered in rich crimsons, pinks, corals, golds, and greens. The hyperrealistic detail and dramatic dark background give it the feel of a Dutch Golden Age still life painting scaled up to building size.',img:'images/murals/2025/reid-jenkins.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:17,a:'Sara Salem',t:'We Are St. Pete',loc:'2180 4th St N',bldg:'LMCU',lat:27.792028,lng:-82.638969,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'sarasalemartsy',bio:'Sara Salem is a St. Petersburg-based mural artist and co-founder of Phi Phi Artland, a creative arts center blending fine art, wellness, and community. She holds a BFA (2011) and brings over 12 years of teaching experience spanning Africa, Asia, and the USA. Beyond murals, Salem is a yoga instructor, Reiki Level II practitioner, and certified art therapist who co-founded Milky Way Retreats. For the 2025 SHINE Origins festival, she led a community mural project at LMCU Bank, inviting local residents to help paint alongside her — one of the festival\'s signature collaborative highlights.',desc:'A large mural on the side of a building featuring a colorful pelican wearing a white baseball cap and reflective sunglasses that show St. Pete landmarks in their lenses. The pelican\'s wings are spread wide in vibrant pinks, oranges, blues, and deep reds. A golden spiral sun radiates in the upper left corner, and "We Are St. Pete" appears in playful navy blue script to the right. Signed "Phi Phi Artland @Sarasalemartsy" at the bottom. The white background keeps the whole piece bright and inviting.',img:'images/murals/2025/sara-salem.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:19,a:'Zulu Painter',t:'',loc:'31st St & 7th Ave S',bldg:'',lat:27.762869,lng:-82.674928,y:2025,cat:'shine',ig:'zulupainter1',bio:'Carlos Culbertson, known as Zulu Painter, is a St. Petersburg-based multimedia artist who works in traditional mediums, body paint, special effects, and scenic art. His motto — "I want to grow Art everywhere" — drives him as he creates "Mindful Murals" across the country. He has worked as a scenic artist for The Science Channel, Disney on Ice, Home Shopping Network, Sea World, and national ad campaigns, and served as a Representative Artist for Visit Florida. A SHINE veteran since 2016, his murals are especially prominent in the Deuces neighborhood, including "Moonbeam Dreams" and "Wisdom, Growth, Progress." He returned for SHINE 2017, 2018, 2024, and 2025 Origins.',desc:'A vibrant mural on a cinder block wall blending multiple styles. The left side features a photorealistic portrait of a young Black woman in profile against a houndstooth pattern with a boombox rendered in grayscale. The center and right side shift to a cartoon aesthetic — a wild-eyed character with a mischievous grin faces off against a massive green alligator with bared teeth, set against a turquoise geometric diamond pattern and black- and-white checkerboard. Colorful polka dots in orange, pink, and yellow punctuate the composition. Signed "zulupainter.com" in the lower right.',img:'images/murals/2025/zulu-painter.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:20,a:'Abys',t:'',loc:'201 17th Street South',bldg:'Modera',lat:27.768439,lng:-82.658011,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'abys_osmoz',bio:'Julien Brouand, known as Abys, is a self-taught French artist from Nancy, born in 1991. Passionate about drawing and cartoons from a young age, he discovered graffiti in 2009. After years practicing with various collectives, he developed his own character-driven style in 2015 — staging lively, narrative, and colorful compositions mixing whimsical characters, decorations, and lettering. For the 2024 SHINE festival, he painted this six-story gator in just four days and had enough time and paint left over to create a bonus crab mural on the back of Anchor Skate Supply nearby.',desc:'A six-story-tall mural on the side of the Modera apartment building depicting a cartoonish, pot-bellied alligator with a mischievous grin, riding a red surfboard through splashing turquoise waves. A pink hibiscus flower sits atop the gator\'s head, and teal smoke curls above. The surfboard reads "SHINE" in stylized lettering. At the base, a triangular logo anchors the composition. The character\'s exaggerated features and vibrant green-on-gray color scheme make it visible from blocks away.',img:'images/murals/2024/abys.jpeg',from:'Nancy, France'},
  {id:22,a:'Dwayne Shepherd & Brian McAllister',t:'The Importance of ART Education',loc:'3535 Central Ave',bldg:'Bell Pharmacy',lat:27.771228,lng:-82.681511,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'dwayneshepherd3499',bio:'Dwayne Shepherd is a visual arts teacher at Osceola Middle School in Seminole, FL, where he has taught for over 22 years and founded a mural club that transformed campus walls with student-painted murals. A graduate of Austin Peay State University, he was named Florida Art Teacher of the Year in 2015 and has been a Pinellas County Teacher of the Year finalist three times. Brian McAllister is an international muralist, illustrator, and visual arts instructor at the Pinellas County Center for the Arts at Gibbs High School. A Ringling College of Art and Design graduate, he founded the Gibbs Mural Club, a 13-year community outreach program with 36 students creating professional public art. His SHINE credits include the 133-foot "Great Futures Start Here" mural on the historic Royal Theater in 2019. Together, Shepherd and McAllister collaborate with art educators statewide through the Florida Art Education Association (FAEA).',desc:'A vibrant marine-themed mural on the side of Bell Pharmacy celebrating art education. The composition centers on an underwater scene with sea turtles swimming among mangrove roots, tropical fish, and coral. Dolphins arc through the water above while the text "The Importance of ART Education" anchors the design. The mural was painted collaboratively with art educators from across Florida during the FAEA annual conference in October 2024 as one of four "Bright Spots" community murals in SHINE\'s 10th anniversary festival.',img:'images/murals/2024/dwayne-shepherd-brian-mcallister.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:23,a:'Emmanuel Jarus',t:'',loc:'226 5th Ave N',bldg:'Walker-Whitney',lat:27.777247,lng:-82.636847,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'youngjarus',bio:'Emmanuel Jarus (b. 1992) is a Canadian muralist and figurative painter based in Toronto. Originally from Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, he transitioned from painting freight trains to large-scale murals around age 19. Largely self-taught with brief studies at the Academy of Realist Art in Toronto, his style blends post-impressionistic influences with unconventional hardware-store materials — acrylic, latex, aerosol, brushes, rollers, and sometimes a broom. He describes his approach as "painting journalism," creating portraiture that emerges organically from the communities he visits. His international credits include the first UN75 "Zero Hunger" mural near United Nations headquarters in Manhattan (2020), festivals in Boulogne-sur-Mer, Calgary, Halifax, and Toronto\'s Graffiti Alley. He is represented by LALA Contemporary gallery.',desc:'A 14-story photorealistic portrait of an enigmatic woman in flowing black garments spanning the entire west-facing wall of the Walker-Whitney building — the largest mural in SHINE\'s 10-year history at roughly 180 feet tall by 60 feet wide. The woman has long brown hair and one hand resting on her chest, gazing out with a serene, mysterious expression against a muted gray-teal background. Jarus intentionally keeps her identity a secret. The figure is a recurring subject he first painted on a seaside structure in Boulogne-sur-Mer, France. Painted with brushes, rollers, and bucket paint over 20 days — interrupted by Hurricane Milton\'s evacuation — in time for SHINE\'s 10th anniversary festival in November 2024.',img:'images/murals/2024/emmanuel-jarus.jpeg',from:'Toronto, Canada'},
  {id:24,a:'Fintan Magee',t:'',loc:'777 3rd Ave North',bldg:'Reflection St. Pete',lat:27.77525833,lng:-82.64443833,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'fintan_magee',bio:'Fintan Magee is an Australian muralist based in Sydney, known for large-scale social realist paintings that tackle environmental themes — water, endangered species, the refugee crisis. He holds a BFA from Griffith University and started as a graffiti writer before shifting to figurative public art. His walls appear in cities from London and Vienna to Buenos Aires and Kyiv, and he\'s shown at Nuart Festival in Stavanger and Aberdeen. His SHINE 2024 mural spans four stories of the Reflection St. Pete apartment building, depicting an underwater scene in cool blues and teals — a submerged figure, a glass bottle, crystal formations, and a pineapple, all rendered with photorealistic precision. The piece plays on the water and submersion themes that run through much of Magee\'s environmental work.',desc:'A four-story mural in shades of blue and teal covers the face of the Reflection St. Pete building. The scene depicts objects and a figure submerged underwater — a glass perfume-style bottle, crystalline formations, and a pineapple float in rippling blue water. The photorealistic rendering captures light refracting through the water surface above. The building\'s "REFLECTION" signage sits just below the mural\'s lower edge.',img:'images/murals/2024/fintan-magee.jpeg',from:'Australia'},
  {id:25,a:'Frankie Gonzalez',t:'',loc:'2606 Fairfield Ave South',bldg:'FloridaRAMA',lat:27.763367,lng:-82.668428,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'frankieg_art',bio:'Francisco "Frankie G" Gonzalez is a Miami-born, Tampa-based mixed-media artist whose work blends comic, urban, and traditional painting techniques into bold, culture-infused compositions rooted in his Cuban and Danish heritage. After attending the Atlanta College of Art, he spent nine years in Salt Lake City before returning to Florida to pursue art full-time. He combines spray paint and latex to create figurative subjects juxtaposed with street art and pop art elements. His public commissions include "Tampa\'s LIGHT" at Tampa Fire Rescue Headquarters and projects for the cities of Tampa, Clearwater, Largo, and St. Petersburg. Commercial clients include ESPN, the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, Norwegian Cruise Lines, and Ducati. He also runs mural camps in local schools and works with Habitat for Humanity and the Down Syndrome Foundation of Florida.',desc:'A wide, energetic mural on the side of FloridaRAMA blending photorealism with street art. At center, a boy in a baseball cap and tan shirt launches a paper airplane, his outstretched arm dissolving into bold black calligraphic strokes and cartoon-style characters. Oversized pink peonies, sunflowers, and white daisies bloom along the bottom, while swirls of pink, yellow, orange, and turquoise fill the background. The composition moves from lush botanical realism on the left through the figurative center to playful abstraction on the right, creating a dynamic sense of childhood imagination taking flight.',img:'images/murals/2024/frankie-gonzalez.jpeg',from:'Tampa, FL'},
  {id:29,a:'NeSpoon',t:'',loc:'601 24th St South',bldg:'Cemex',lat:27.764411,lng:-82.666214,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'nes.nespoon',bio:'NeSpoon (Elzbieta Dymna) is a Polish street artist based in Warsaw whose signature medium is lace — traditional textile patterns rendered at monumental scale on building facades and pressed into ceramic pieces installed on streets. Her artist name comes from the famous line in The Matrix. She began her street art career in 2009 after discovering that pressing lace into clay was a traditional decorative technique, and has since created work in over 100 cities across 40 countries on five continents. At each location she researches local lace-making traditions through museums and community conversations. Her work has appeared at the Louvre-Lens, EXPO Dubai 2020, the European Parliament in Brussels, and the Urban Nation Biennale in Berlin. She won the ARTAQ Prize in France in 2011 and 2012 and was selected for Urban Nation\'s Fresh A.I.R. residency in Berlin in 2018.',desc:'A wide mural on the Cemex building featuring NeSpoon\'s signature lace patterns in white and pale blue against a deep plum-purple background. Intricate medallions with floral and geometric motifs occupy the left and center, their delicate threadwork rendered with illusory three-dimensional depth through careful shading and layering. The right side transitions into flowing, organic swirls that evoke wind or waves. The effect transforms the industrial concrete wall into what appears to be an enormous draped lace textile. Signed "NeSpoon" in the lower left corner.',img:'images/murals/2024/nespoon.jpeg',from:'Warsaw, Poland'},
  {id:30,a:'Quinn Cale',t:'',loc:'225 2nd Ave North',bldg:'Main Grove',lat:27.77370833,lng:-82.6362,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'quinnsessential',bio:'Quinn Cale is a Tampa-based painter originally from Delaware whose work channels early-2000s childhood nostalgia into bold, colorful compositions. She previously worked at Apple, an experience that led her to experiment with augmented reality overlays on her paintings using Adobe Aero — viewers can point an iPad at the canvas and see digital elements come to life. Her SHINE 2024 mural at Main Grove features a multicolored cat in vivid neon hues pouncing toward a pixelated mouse cursor and a retro-styled pixel hand pointer. The gaming references and rainbow palette are pure Cale — pop culture nostalgia meets street art energy.',desc:'A large cat rendered in electric purples, teals, oranges, and pinks leaps across the wall, chasing a pixelated orange mouse and a retro cursor hand icon. The cat\'s fur is broken into bold color blocks that read like a neon stained-glass window. The whole piece pops against a dark teal and sage background.',img:'images/murals/2024/quinn-cale.jpeg',from:'Tampa, FL'},
  {id:31,a:'Stevie Shao',t:'',loc:'850 5th Ave South',bldg:'Volunteers of America',lat:27.765203,lng:-82.646683,y:2024,cat:'shine',ig:'stepfrae',bio:'Stevie Shao is a second-generation Chinese-American illustrator and muralist born and raised in Seattle. She studied interior design at Seattle Pacific University, where an illustration course with Rachell Sumpter sparked her artistic path. After being laid off during COVID-19 in 2020, she transitioned to full-time art, quickly becoming one of Seattle\'s most in-demand public artists. Her style blends folk art, Chinese ceramics, and traditional American tattoo influences into ornate, maximalist compositions filled with plants, animals, and mythical creatures. Clients include Starbucks, REI, Google, Nordstrom, Sub Pop Records, and the Seattle Kraken, for whom she designed the 2022 Women in Hockey jersey. Fashion designer Anna Sui featured her work in her Spring/Summer 2021 collection. She was named one of Seattle Magazine\'s "25 Most Influential" in 2023.',desc:'A multi-story mural on the side of the Volunteers of America building depicting a sinuous, serpentine dragon in bold navy blue, red, gold, and turquoise against a white background. The dragon coils upward across the full height of the building, its body decorated with pink scalloped scales and chartreuse dots. Two stylized birds with spread wings — one near the top and one at the bottom — intertwine with the dragon\'s twisting form. Blue flames curl from the dragon\'s mouth. The flat, graphic style draws on Chinese folk art and traditional tattoo aesthetics. Signed "Stevie Shao 24" in the lower right corner.',img:'images/murals/2024/stevie-shao.jpeg',from:'Seattle, WA'},
  {id:37,a:'Bryan Beyung & James Lee Chiahan',t:'When the Sun is Up, the Moon is Absent!',loc:'2875 7th Ave S',bldg:'Stewart Moving & Storage',lat:27.762889,lng:-82.673758,y:2023,cat:'shine',ig:'bryanbeyung',bio:'Bryan Beyung (王永財) is a Sino-Cambodian visual artist born in Montreal to a family of Chinese-Cambodian refugees. He studied graphic design at Cégep Marie-Victorin and color theory and muralism at Galería LaRoja in Seville, Spain. His work explores immigration, diasporic heritage, and migratory flows, blending neo-muralism, post-graffiti, and contemporary painting. Notable projects include "The Sea Keeper," the first mural on a Canadian bulk carrier, and public works across the US, Canada, Haiti, France, Morocco, and Cambodia. James Lee Chiahan (李佳翰, b. 1990) is a Taiwanese-Canadian artist from Tainan, Taiwan, now based in Montreal. Largely self-taught in oil painting, he creates emotionally resonant work exploring memory, closeness, and distance. His editorial illustration clients include The New Yorker, The Atlantic, The Washington Post, The New York Times, and Apple. He won the 2024 Canadian Magazine Awards Grand Prize for Cover Art. The two share a studio in Montreal.',desc:'A two-panel mural on the Stewart Moving & Storage building. The left side features a large black circle on a golden background containing a white tree silhouette and crescent moon — based on a drawing by six-year-old Amelia Kien — with the word "ABSENT" below and colorful childlike figures along the bottom painted by the Kien family. The right side shows a photorealistic sunset landscape with four family members — two adults and two children — standing on a hillside, connected by a red textile panel with traditional patterns. A navy blue band along the base depicts fish silhouettes. The mural tells the story of the Kien family, who fled Cambodia in 1987 and eventually settled near Bradenton, Florida, just minutes from this wall.',img:'images/murals/2023/bryan-beyung-james-lee-chiahan.jpeg',from:'Montreal, Canada'},
  {id:39,a:'Chris Dyer',t:'Ride on the sPEACEship!',loc:'2875 7th Ave S',bldg:'Stewart Moving & Storage',lat:27.762825,lng:-82.672553,y:2023,cat:'shine',ig:'chris_dyer',bio:'Chris Dyer (b. 1979) is a Peruvian-Canadian visionary artist now based in St. Petersburg/Gulfport, Florida. Born in Ottawa, he grew up in Lima, Peru before returning to Canada at 17, eventually studying illustration at Dawson College in Montreal. A leading figure of the North American visionary art movement, his style fuses psychedelic imagery, Incan and pre-Columbian influences, sacred geometry, and 1980s-90s skate culture aesthetics. He has painted murals in 44+ countries, including at the Bob Marley Museum in Jamaica, the Beatles Ashram in India, and the STRAAT Museum in Amsterdam. He founded the Positive Creations brand in 2003 and has published two art books through Schiffer and Last Gasp. He teaches workshops at the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts, the National Gallery of Canada, and The Chapel of Sacred Mirrors (CoSM).',desc:'A panoramic cosmic scene against a starry black background on Stewart Moving & Storage. A wildly detailed spaceship made of interlocking creatures, tentacles, and geometric patterns blasts across the wall, trailing rainbow exhaust flames and lightning bolts. The vessel is piloted by psychedelic characters with multiple eyes and Incan-inspired headdresses, one flashing a peace sign from inside a blue bubble cockpit. "Positive Creations" floats above in rainbow lettering, "PEACE PLEASE" appears in a speech bubble at right, and a smiling sun face radiates in the upper right corner. Saturn, UFOs, and alien faces orbit the composition. Signed "Chris Dyer" at left and "LOVE!" in pink at lower right.',img:'images/murals/2023/chris-dyer.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:42,a:'Greater Public Studio',t:'Dive Into Discovery',loc:'6th Ave S & 2nd St S',bldg:'USF Campus',lat:27.76005333,lng:-82.637055,y:2023,cat:'shine',ig:'greaterpublicstudio',bio:'Greater Public Studio is a Tampa-based creative team that designs large-scale murals and visual environments. Founded with a focus on making public spaces more engaging, GPS has taken on projects ranging from building-sized paintings to immersive installations across Florida and beyond. Their 2023 SHINE piece at the USF St. Pete campus brought a burst of color to the university district with "Dive Into Discovery," a vibrant scene depicting an imaginative community landscape full of whimsical architectural forms and figures.',desc:'A colorful, illustrative mural spanning a large wall near the USF St. Pete campus. The composition features a fantastical townscape with stacked buildings, winding paths, and small figures exploring the scene. Bright blues, oranges, and greens fill the design in a style that feels like an oversized storybook illustration.',img:'images/murals/2023/greater-public-studio.jpeg',from:'Tampa, FL'},
  {id:46,a:'Loretta Lizzio',t:'The Sirens Call',loc:'2875 7th Ave S',bldg:'Stewart Moving & Storage',lat:27.762869,lng:-82.67305,y:2023,cat:'shine',ig:'loretta_lizzio',bio:'Loretta Lizzio (b. 1986) is a Greek-Australian painter, photographer, and muralist based in Melbourne. She honed her artistic sensitivity through professional experience in publishing, photography, and advertising before dedicating herself full-time to fine art and murals. Her ethereal works layer oil, acrylic, resin, gold leaf, and intricate line work to explore themes of Greek mythology, romanticism, nature, and the female figure. She is the first female artist commissioned for the Hellenic Museum\'s Dialogue Series, creating "Well Behaved Women" — a three-part mural of fearless women from ancient Greek history. Her work has appeared at the Brisbane Street Art Festival, Vancouver Mural Festival, and Wall to Wall Festival, and in galleries including Haven, Nucleus, Beinart, and Outre. She has collaborated commercially with New Balance, Wacom, and Toyota.',desc:'A wide mural on the Stewart Moving & Storage building depicting three women as sirens from Greek mythology against a deep teal-green background. The figures emerge from lush green foliage, their pale skin overlaid with intricate leaf patterns and delicate line work that makes them appear to grow from the plants themselves. Their dark hair flows and intertwines across the top of the composition, creating a canopy effect. The sirens gaze outward with serene yet subtly unsettling expressions — beautiful and sinister at once. Signed "Loretta Lizzio" in the upper right corner.',img:'images/murals/2023/loretta-lizzio.jpeg',from:'Melbourne, Australia'},
  {id:47,a:'Max Sansing',t:'Shining Hope',loc:'401 5th St N',bldg:'Trinity Lutheran Church',lat:27.777006,lng:-82.639969,y:2023,cat:'shine',ig:'maxsansing',bio:'Max Sansing is a Chicago-based fine artist and muralist who grew up on the South Side in the Avalon Park neighborhood. He began making art at 14 through graffiti, joining crews like Def Con 5 and Recking Krew, before formal training at the American Academy of Art. His style fuses the color-drenched dynamism of street art with the technical elegance of photorealism, working in oil, acrylic, spray paint, and enamel. His commissions include portraits of President Obama, Walter Payton, and Fred Hampton, plus projects for Nike/Virgil Abloh, the NBA All-Star Weekend, and Chicago Fire FC. He won "Best Street Artist" in Chicago\'s Best of Chicago awards (2017) and has exhibited at POW! WOW! Hawaii, Scope Miami Beach, and UNITY in Dubai. He is represented by Thinkspace Projects in Los Angeles and deeply committed to expanding arts access on Chicago\'s South Side.',desc:'A multi-story portrait on the north face of Trinity Lutheran Church depicting a young Black woman gazing outward with quiet intensity. Her face is rendered in photorealistic detail with warm brown skin tones, while her body dissolves into swirling, psychedelic layers of green, turquoise, purple, and gold — evoking geode cross-sections and topographic forms. A large hibiscus flower in peach and violet blooms at her shoulder, and deep blue flowers anchor the bottom of the composition. A red archway silhouette with palm trees appears within the flowing forms, and a bird silhouette flies above. A SHINE plaque is visible at the base.',img:'images/murals/2023/max-sansing.jpeg',from:'Chicago, IL'},
  {id:120,a:'Melanie Posner',t:'',loc:'',bldg:'',lat:27.772,lng:-82.6491,y:2023,cat:'commercial',ig:'therealmelpoz',bio:'Melanie Posner is an LA-based muralist originally from Pennsylvania who earned her BFA from the University of Tampa. She\'s known for vibrant, photorealistic portraits of women, and her client list includes Walt Disney World, Amazon Prime, and TikTok — for whom she painted a 40-foot mural in the heart of Hollywood. Her 2023 St. Pete mural features a woman\'s face in oversized reflective sunglasses with bright pink lips, set against a playful background of colorful polka dots on teal. The sunglasses reflect what appears to be the St. Pete waterfront, tying the portrait to its location.',desc:'A photorealistic woman\'s face fills the wall, wearing large reflective sunglasses that mirror a waterfront skyline scene. Bright pink lips and warm skin tones contrast with the cool teal background, which is dotted with oversized polka dots in pink, gold, red, and light blue. The piece wraps around windows that are incorporated into the design. Palm trees frame the mural on either side.',img:'images/murals/commercial/unknown-1506.jpeg',from:'Los Angeles, CA'},
  {id:52,a:'蔡陈林',t:'The Path We Came / 我们来的路',loc:'1927 4th Ave S',bldg:'Lantmännen Unibake',lat:27.768364,lng:-82.659783,y:2023,cat:'shine',ig:'chenlin.cai',bio:'Chenlin Cai (蔡陈林, b. 1984) is a Chinese-American visual artist based in Philadelphia. Born in a fishing village in Fujian province, China, he holds MFAs from both Tsinghua University in Beijing and the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts (PAFA). He immigrated to the US in 2014. His work innovatively combines traditional Chinese ink painting with contemporary Western oil painting techniques, exploring the tension of navigating Eastern and Western cultures. Major commissions include "The Past Supporting the Future," a 54-foot crane mural on the Crane Community Center in Philadelphia\'s Chinatown created with Mural Arts Philadelphia, and an installation at Philadelphia International Airport. He received the "Excellent Artist Award" at the Eye Art 2017 exhibition at United Nations Headquarters and the Coverly Smith Prize at Woodmere Art Museum. He served as Commissioner on the Pennsylvania Governor\'s Advisory Commission on Asian Pacific American Affairs (2022-2023).',desc:'A wide mural on the Lantmännen Unibake building depicting three Chinese American railroad laborers rendered in blue-gray tones against a dramatic sunset of deep orange, gold, and purple. The three figures — one holding a staff, one reading a letter, one planting a flower with his hat removed — represent family longing, hope, and resilience. Behind them, golden mountain peaks evoke the Sierra Nevada, with a setting sun and crescent moon embodying the duality of aspiration and homesickness. A steam locomotive and train cars wind along railroad tracks at right. The mural reimagines Chinese laborers who built the First Transcontinental Railroad but were excluded from its 1869 completion photographs. Created in partnership with the James Museum\'s "From Far East to West" exhibition.',img:'images/murals/2023/chenlin-cai.jpeg',from:'Philadelphia, PA'},
  {id:57,a:'Ben Johnston',t:'Rise',loc:'1010 Central Ave',bldg:'',lat:27.770697,lng:-82.649575,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'ben_johnston',bio:'Originally from Cape Town, South Africa, Ben Johnston now works out of Toronto creating typographic murals at massive scale. He\'s known for turning simple words into architectural illusions — his signature style uses isometric 3D letterforms with precise color gradients that make flat walls look like they\'re popping off the building. He\'s painted walls on six continents and shows fine art in galleries internationally.',desc:'A towering multi-story mural on the side of an apartment building spelling "RISE" in massive 3D block letters. The isometric letterforms are rendered in graduating shades of cerulean, sky blue, and white against a deep blue background, with crisp shadows giving the typography a sculptural, floating quality. Signed "Ben" in white script at the lower left. The mural dominates the building\'s full height, visible from blocks away along Central Avenue.',img:'images/murals/2022/ben-johnston.jpeg',from:'Toronto, Canada'},
  {id:59,a:'Dream Weaver',t:'',loc:'1510 1st Ave. N.',bldg:'',lat:27.771567,lng:-82.65477,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'dream.weavin',bio:'Taylor "Dreamweaver" Smith is a St. Petersburg-based street artist and muralist whose work invokes a sense of reverence for the natural world. Her evolving style integrates expressive abstraction and realism to capture the spirit of life through light and color — often featuring portraiture, vivid patterns, and striking color combinations. She creates murals, canvas works, and live painting activations for communities and brands both locally and nationwide.',desc:'A massive wall-sized explosion of color — a hybrid floral-phoenix form rendered in neon pinks, fiery oranges, deep purples, cerulean blues, and electric teals against a dark blue background. Feathered petals radiate outward from the center while swirling organic tendrils and tropical leaves frame the edges. Signed "Dreamweaver" in stylized script at the lower left. A SHINE festival plaque is visible at the base.',img:'images/murals/2022/dreamweaver.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:60,a:'Egypt Hagan',t:'',loc:'299 Dr MLK Jr St N',bldg:'George F. Young',lat:27.77535,lng:-82.6464,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'graffitiegypt',bio:'Egypt Hagan, who paints under the name Graffiti Egypt, is an LA-born muralist now based in Arizona. She\'s known for luminous, large-scale portraits that use bold color and gold tones to tell stories about identity and resilience. Her work has been exhibited internationally and featured in publications including the Sun-Sentinel and PRINT Magazine. Her 2022 SHINE mural on the George F. Young building features two faces in profile wreathed in roses, filling the multi-story wall with the kind of intimacy that\'s hard to pull off at that scale. The warm palette and painterly brushwork make it feel more like a gallery piece than a typical building mural.',desc:'Two faces in profile fill the multi-story wall of the George F. Young building, surrounded by roses and soft washes of warm color. The portraits are rendered with expressive, painterly brushwork — detailed enough to read as specific individuals but loose enough to feel like fine art rather than photorealism. Roses and floral elements weave around and between the two figures.',img:'images/murals/2022/egypt-hagan.jpeg',from:'Arizona'},
  {id:61,a:'Imagine',t:'',loc:'240 Dr MLK Jr St N',bldg:'RetroTiques',lat:27.77412,lng:-82.647112,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'imagine876',bio:'Imagine is a Kathmandu-born artist who fuses Sanskrit calligraphy with graffiti energy. Her large-scale murals turn ancient Nepalese script into repeating visual mantras — bold, rhythmic compositions that read as both sacred text and abstract pattern. She works across painting, sculpture, and public walls internationally.',desc:'A long parking-lot wall painted solid hot pink, covered with repeating columns of gold Sanskrit-inspired calligraphy. The metallic gold letterforms cascade downward in ornate clusters, with subtler red and pink swirls layered underneath. The effect is meditative and hypnotic — the same sacred text echoing across the entire wall like a visual chant.',img:'images/murals/2022/imagine.jpeg',from:'Kathmandu, Nepal'},
  {id:62,a:'James Bullough',t:'',loc:'2201 Central Ave.',bldg:'Central Neurology',lat:27.771253,lng:-82.663567,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'james_bullough',bio:'James Bullough grew up in Washington, DC, where early exposure to graffiti culture shaped his visual sensibility. He taught himself oil painting by studying Old Masters, then moved to Berlin where he now lives and works. His signature style splits photorealistic figures into fractured geometric ribbons — precise portraits shattered by bold abstract slashes. He paints both massive outdoor walls and studio canvases, with landmark murals in New Zealand, Sweden, France, Ukraine, and across the US. His gallery shows regularly sell out.',desc:'A multi-story mural on the side of a building depicting a woman in a crimson dress, her body fragmented into sweeping ribbon-like shards that scatter across a dark black background. The photorealistic figure — head tilted back, arms outstretched — appears to be dissolving or reassembling mid-leap. Deep navy blue, coral red, and muted lavender geometric strips weave through the composition, creating a sense of explosive movement against the void.',img:'images/murals/2022/james-bullough.jpeg',from:'Berlin, Germany'},
  {id:64,a:'Jeff Williams',t:'',loc:'511 Dr. MLK Jr St. N.',bldg:'Myoblast Strength',lat:27.77776333,lng:-82.6466,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'sunsigns.stpete',bio:'Jeff Williams is a St. Petersburg native who runs Sun Signs, a traditional sign painting shop in the city. His work is steeped in mid-century design — hand-drawn letterforms, 1950s advertising aesthetics, and vintage tattoo flash — and he\'s painted the sign for Sunken Gardens, one of Florida\'s oldest roadside attractions. He\'s been featured on PBS WEDU\'s Arts Plus. His SHINE 2022 mural at Myoblast Strength is a love letter to old Florida tourism — stacked horizontal bands reading "Florida Souvenirs," "St. Petersburg," "the sun... the sea... you & me," "Tampa Bay," and "Sunshine 360 Days a Year," all painted in vintage postcard style with retro illustrations. It looks like it could have been on a highway billboard in 1955.',desc:'A tall wall painted as a stack of vintage Florida tourism signs in bold primary colors. From top to bottom: "Florida SOUVENIRS" with palm trees, "ST. PETERSBURG" in large white block letters on black, "the sun... the sea... you & me — THE SUNSHINE CITY" on red with pin-up illustrations and oranges, "FLORIDA" in classic postcard lettering, "Tampa Bay" in red script with a pelican mascot, and "Sunshine 360 Days A Year" with a retro couple in green. Every detail is hand-painted in authentic mid-century sign style.',img:'images/murals/2022/jeff-williams.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:65,a:'MadC',t:'',loc:'1010 Central Ave.',bldg:'',lat:27.770712,lng:-82.649567,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'mad_c1',bio:'Claudia Walde, known as MadC, is a German graffiti artist and painter with nearly three decades in the game. Nicknamed "The Mad One" for her fearless approach, she\'s built an international reputation for translating the speed and energy of graffiti calligraphy into large-scale abstract compositions. Her work layers translucent sweeps of color that overlap and glow where they intersect — part street art, part color-field painting. She works on both massive outdoor walls and studio canvases.',desc:'A multi-story abstract mural on the side of an apartment building. Sweeping translucent ribbons of hot pink, cyan, orange, and white crisscross at sharp angles over a vivid yellow background. Where the color bands overlap they create new hues — purple where pink meets blue, warm peach where orange meets white. The effect is like looking through stacked sheets of colored glass. White paint splatter near the top right adds a calligraphic flourish.',img:'images/murals/2022/madc.jpeg',from:'Germany'},
  {id:66,a:'Marina Capdevila',t:'',loc:'601 1st Ave. N.',bldg:'The Sage',lat:27.771775,lng:-82.642442,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'marinacapdevila',bio:'Marina Capdevila is a Barcelona-born muralist who studied Fine Arts in her hometown and at the Willem de Kooning Academy in Rotterdam, where she first got into street art. Over the past decade she\'s painted walls across the Americas and Europe — from Brazil and Mexico to Belgium, Croatia, and the UK. Her style is playful and surreal: oversized, rubbery characters with exaggerated features interacting in absurd scenes full of warmth and humor.',desc:'A two-story wall dominated by a crowd of surreal orange-skinned characters in various states of mischief. On the left, a figure in a beret and sunglasses clutches a boombox. In the center, an enormous face wearing oversized reflective shades holds a lobster. On the right, a figure in a bucket hat dangles a fish on a line while a pale ghost-like creature peeks out between them. The palette is almost entirely warm oranges, creams, and golds against a yellow-gold upper band with tiny palm tree silhouettes. Signed "Marina Capdevila" at the upper left.',img:'images/murals/2022/marina-capdevila.jpeg',from:'Barcelona, Spain'},
  {id:68,a:'Reginald O\'Neal',t:'',loc:'701 3rd St. S.',bldg:'USF Piano Man Building',lat:27.76296167,lng:-82.63767167,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'reginaldo.neal',bio:'Reginald O\'Neal is a Miami-born painter who grew up in Overtown and trained under mentor Alejandro Dorda. His work has been acquired by Perez Art Museum Miami and ICA Miami, he\'s represented by Vielmetter Los Angeles gallery, and he was named to the Artsy Vanguard in 2021. He\'s completed murals in Austria, Norway, Spain, and the Dominican Republic. His SHINE 2022 mural on the USF Piano Man Building is a monochromatic composition depicting historian John Henrik Clarke in a suit alongside scenes of the Mundari tribe of South Sudan — figures with long-horned cattle and a fisherman working nets. The entire piece is rendered in blacks, whites, and warm sepia tones with classical oil-painting technique.',desc:'A sweeping black-and-white mural spanning the full wall. A suited man — historian John Henrik Clarke — sits as the central figure, painted with photorealistic precision. Behind him, silhouetted scenes show Mundari tribespeople tending long-horned cattle and casting fishing nets. The monochromatic palette and classical brushwork give the piece the weight of a museum painting at building scale.',img:'images/murals/2022/reginald-oneal.jpeg',from:'Miami, FL'},
  {id:69,a:'Sydney Prusso',t:'Look Inside',loc:'533 28th St. S.',bldg:'Seriously Strong Training',lat:27.765762,lng:-82.671425,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'sydneyprusso',bio:'Sydney Prusso is a St. Petersburg illustrator, lettering artist, and muralist. Her style pulls from 1960s and \'70s poster art — groovy hand-lettering, warm retro palettes, and flowing psychedelic compositions. Much of her work explores themes of mental health and the outdoors, wrapped in colorful, feel-good imagery that\'s impossible not to smile at.',desc:'The entire side of a peaked-roof building wrapped in retro psychedelic lettering spelling "Outside" and "Look Inside" in chunky, rounded \'70s-style typography. The letters are layered in pinks, oranges, chartreuse, white, and maroon against a purple background. Colorful butterflies — a large pink-and-red one at center, smaller ones floating above — are scattered between the words. Sparkle stars dot the upper peak. The overall vibe is a vintage concert poster blown up to building scale.',img:'images/murals/2022/sydney-prusso.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:73,a:'Vitale Bros',t:'',loc:'3190 75th St. N.',bldg:'Parc',lat:27.77245333,lng:-82.643495,y:2022,cat:'shine',ig:'vitalebros',bio:'The Vitale Brothers — Johnny and Paul — are a St. Petersburg muralist duo who\'ve been part of the local art scene for years. They\'re known for large-scale character paintings with a playful, pop-culture-heavy approach that makes their walls some of the most photographed in the city. Their 2022 SHINE piece at Parc features a lineup of cartoon characters rendered in the Vitales\' bold, graphic style, turning the building wall into a crowd-pleasing photo spot.',desc:'A row of SpongeBob SquarePants characters fills the wall in the Vitale Brothers\' bold, graphic mural style. The familiar cartoon figures are painted at building scale with clean outlines and flat, saturated colors that pop against the building exterior. It\'s become one of the more popular photo-op walls in the area.',img:'images/murals/2022/vitale-bros.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:34,a:'Zulu Painter',t:'',loc:'Arlington Ave N',bldg:'CASA Family Justice Center',lat:27.7726,lng:-82.64923,y:2022,cat:'commercial',ig:'zulupainter1',bio:'Zulu Painter (Carlos Culbertson) is a St. Petersburg-based multimedia artist whose "Mindful Murals" appear on buildings across the US. His practice spans traditional painting, special effects, and scenic art, and he\'s been part of SHINE since 2017 when he painted "Thirst" for the festival. His vibrant, community-focused work aims to uplift through color and representation. The CASA Family Justice Center mural was commissioned by philanthropists Willi Rudowsky and Hal Freedman through a request-for-proposals process, completed ahead of the center\'s October 2022 grand opening. It spans two buildings on Arlington Avenue, two blocks north of Central, and was designed to create a welcoming environment for domestic violence survivors arriving at the center.',desc:'Four diverse faces fill the two-story CASA Family Justice Center building, representing different demographics affected by domestic violence. On one side, a woman cradles a baby, with words embedded in the curls of her hair — "Drive, Bravery, Family, Growth, Hope, Empathy, Love, Community, Wisdom, Faith, Create, and Unity." The other side depicts a young woman extending a helping hand and a young man making direct eye contact. Colorful geometric patterns, blue polka dots, swirling vines, and flowers in purples and golds surround the figures. A pathway of white polka dots and purple triangles crosses Arlington Avenue as part of the design.',img:'images/murals/2024/zulu-painter.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:75,a:'Bakpak Durden',t:'',loc:'919 1st Ave. N.',bldg:'The Bends',lat:27.77227,lng:-82.64756667,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'bakpakdurden',bio:'Bakpak Durden is a self-taught Detroit artist working across oil, acrylic, graphite, and photography. Their hyperrealistic work fuses Baroque and Afro-Surrealist influences, and they\'ve shown at Cranbrook Art Museum\'s inaugural Fresh Paint series, Paradigm Gallery in Philadelphia, and Muskegon Museum of Art. They received the Torch of Wisdom Foundation Cultural Arts Rising Star award in 2024. The SHINE 2021 mural on The Bends is a dark, dramatic vanitas piece — a human jaw and skull emerge from swirling dark greens and blacks, with the text "TELL ME HOW YOU FEEL" visible in the upper corner. The entire wall reads like something out of a Baroque gallery, not on the side of a bar.',desc:'A dark, moody mural stretches across the long wall of The Bends. On a near-black background, a skull and exposed jawbone with visible teeth emerge from tangled, organic forms in deep greens and grays. The text "TELL ME HOW YOU FEEL" appears in the upper right corner. The hyperrealistic rendering and somber palette give it the gravity of a classical vanitas painting at massive scale.',img:'images/murals/2021/bakpak-durden.jpeg',from:'Detroit, MI'},
  {id:78,a:'Emily Ding',t:'',loc:'100 7th St. S.',bldg:'Rob Graham Enterprise',lat:27.77026667,lng:-82.64296667,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'_emilyding',bio:'Emily Ding is a Houston-based muralist known for large-scale paintings of animals rendered with a classicist\'s attention to fur and feather and a surrealist\'s sense of composition. She\'s painted walls across the US — Sacramento, Oakland, DC, Salt Lake City, Flint — and internationally in China, and was featured in Houston\'s Mini Murals project and Michigan\'s Bright Walls festival. Her SHINE 2021 mural at Rob Graham Enterprise features a sleeping fawn curled up among white blossoms, painted in rich naturalistic detail against a deep forest-green background. The piece has a quiet tenderness to it, with the young deer nestled into roots and foliage as if the building wall were a woodland floor.',desc:'A young fawn sleeps curled in a gentle pose, its spotted fur rendered with painterly realism. White flowers bloom from the deer\'s back and around its body, growing up toward a window that\'s incorporated into the design. The deep emerald-green background gives the whole wall the feeling of a forest clearing. Emily Ding\'s signature is visible in the lower right.',img:'images/murals/2021/emily-ding.jpeg',from:'Houston, TX'},
  {id:80,a:'Greg Mike',t:'',loc:'915 1st Ave. N.',bldg:'Goldman Wetzel',lat:27.77231167,lng:-82.64716333,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'gregmike',bio:'Greg Mike is an Atlanta-based artist and designer known for his character "Larry Loudmouf" and a hyper-saturated cartoon style that lands somewhere between vintage animation and pop surrealism. Beyond walls, he runs MADPOP — a line of designer toys and collectibles — and has had solo shows at ABV Gallery and painted projects for Moxy Hotels. His 2021 SHINE mural on the Goldman Wetzel building is pure Greg Mike — a packed crowd of grinning, bug-eyed characters in neon pinks and acid greens with "SMILE" running across the center. It\'s one of those walls where the energy is impossible to ignore from the sidewalk.',desc:'A massive wall covered edge-to-edge with Greg Mike\'s signature cartoon characters — bug-eyed, grinning figures in electric pinks, greens, and yellows. The word "SMILE" runs across the center in bold lettering, surrounded by the crowd of manic, playful characters that make the building impossible to walk past without looking.',img:'images/murals/2021/greg-mike.jpeg',from:'Atlanta, GA'},
  {id:82,a:'Jared Wright',t:'Harmony',loc:'670 Central Ave.',bldg:'Colony Grill',lat:27.77083333,lng:-82.64322833,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'jaredwright',bio:'Jared Wright is a Tampa Bay painter and illustrator whose style lands somewhere between Dali and an illustrated storybook. His SHINE 2021 mural on Colony Grill was his first-ever wall piece, and he was later selected for the 2024 Tampa Bay Rays Artist Series with work displayed inside Tropicana Field. The Colony Grill mural, titled "Harmony," features a dreamlike composition of an owl, a serpentine creature, and flowing organic forms in muted corals, sage greens, and teals. A moon floats among the intertwined figures, creating the kind of surreal, gently weird scene Wright is known for.',desc:'A surreal scene fills the Colony Grill wall with smooth, rounded organic forms in muted corals, sage, and teal. An owl with large dark eyes perches near a crescent moon while a snake-like creature winds through the composition. Leaf shapes, clouds, and celestial elements float through the scene, all rendered in soft, flat color fields with clean outlines.',img:'images/murals/2021/jared-wright.jpeg',from:'Tampa Bay, FL'},
  {id:83,a:'Jason Harvin',t:'',loc:'1211 1st Ave. N.',bldg:'Rick Noll Properties',lat:27.772442,lng:-82.650938,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'waywardwalls',bio:'Jason Harvin is a self-taught geometric abstraction artist who left a corporate career in 2022 to paint full time through his company Wayward Walls. His hard-edged style layers triangles, circles, and stripes into dense optical compositions that pulse with energy. Featured on HGTV\'s 100 Day Dream Home, his work can be found across homes and businesses in Tampa Bay. He\'s painted walls and intersection murals for SHINE across St. Petersburg.',desc:'A wide commercial building wrapped in interlocking geometric shapes — overlapping triangles, concentric circles, and bold diagonal stripes in saturated blue, orange, red, yellow, black, and white. A large red triangle dominates the center, framed by concentric blue-and-orange rings. A bright yellow half-circle anchors the bottom edge. Black-and-white striped bands slice through the composition at sharp angles, while smaller geometric motifs fill every remaining gap. Palm trees along the base add scale to the Op Art explosion.',img:'images/murals/2021/jason-harvin.jpeg',from:'Tampa, FL'},
  {id:86,a:'Leo Gomez',t:'Can\'t Thank You Enough',loc:'744 6th Ave. S.',bldg:'Bayfront Health St. Pete',lat:27.76399667,lng:-82.64393667,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'leogomezstudio',bio:'Leo Gomez launched his eponymous studio in St. Petersburg in 2017, focusing on hand lettering, sign painting, and large-format murals. His client list runs from Disney Springs and the St. Pete/Clearwater International Airport to local spots like Green Bench Brewing and Tombolo Books. His SHINE 2021 piece at Bayfront Health reads "Can\'t Thank You Enough" in flowing gold script across a deep navy blue wall — a tribute to healthcare workers painted with the precision and flourish of a trained sign painter.',desc:'Elegant gold script lettering spelling "Can\'t Thank You Enough" fills the entire wall of a building adjacent to Bayfront Health. The flowing cursive letterforms are painted on a rich navy blue background, with decorative swashes and flourishes extending from each word. "Leo Gomez Studio" is signed in the upper right corner.',img:'images/murals/2021/leo-gomez.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:87,a:'Michael Fatutoa',t:'',loc:'2060 1st Ave. S.',bldg:'Grayspeed',lat:27.769725,lng:-82.661583,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'samoan_mike',bio:'Michael Fatutoa grew up on the island of Tutuila in eastern Samoa and was raised in Hawaii before settling in Tampa Bay. A full-time tattoo artist at Sacred Tatau in Tampa, he draws on the ancient Samoan tradition of tatau — hand-tapped geometric patterns passed down through generations — and translates those motifs into large-scale murals. His work also pulls from broader Polynesian visual traditions including carvings and tapa cloth designs, bringing Pacific Island heritage to Florida walls.',desc:'Two massive sea creatures face each other on a flat gray wall. On the left, a hammerhead shark rendered in teal and black, its entire body filled with intricate Polynesian tatau patterns — spirals, chevrons, and layered geometric bands that follow the contours of its form. On the right, a sea turtle in black and white, its shell packed with bold angular motifs including step patterns and diamond shapes, with small teal accents at the flippers. The two animals appear to be circling each other, filling the wall from edge to edge.',img:'images/murals/2021/michael-fatutoa.jpeg',from:'Tampa Bay, FL'},
  {id:89,a:'Mwanel Pierre-Louis',t:'',loc:'1100 1st Ave. N.',bldg:'Green Bench Brewing',lat:27.77184167,lng:-82.65008667,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'mwanel1_l',bio:'Mwanel Pierre-Louis is a Miami-based painter born in New York to Haitian parents. He studied at New World School of the Arts in Miami and the Art Center College of Design in Pasadena, and has since built a client roster that includes Adidas, Jack Daniel\'s, Foot Locker, Puma, the Miami Dolphins, and the Florida Panthers. His paintings have shown at Scope Art Fair during Art Basel and at POW!WOW! Hawaii. His 2021 SHINE portrait on the side of Green Bench Brewing features a woman with flowing locs against layered washes of warm color. The piece shows his signature approach — photorealistic faces dissolving into loose, expressive abstraction around the edges.',desc:'A striking portrait of a woman with long locs dominates the side of Green Bench Brewing. The face is rendered with photorealistic detail while the background dissolves into expressive washes of warm oranges, reds, and earth tones. The contrast between the precise portrait work and the loose, painterly surroundings gives the piece real presence from across the street.',img:'images/murals/2021/mwanel-pierre-louis.jpeg',from:'Miami, FL'},
  {id:93,a:'Woes Martin',t:'',loc:'2343 Emerson Ave. S.',bldg:'New Dawn Coffee Co 2',lat:27.765862,lng:-82.665778,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'woes',bio:'Aaron "Woes" Martin is an LA-based multidisciplinary artist known for his signature angry-eyed panda bears — part menacing, part adorable. Originally a graffiti writer, he evolved into aerosol muralism, acrylic painting, designer toys, and resin sculpture, bringing his snarling pandas to walls and galleries across the globe. He\'s also a DJ and puppeteer. Despite the ferocious faces in his work, Woes brings a laid-back aloha energy to everything he does.',desc:'A long warehouse wall covered in a pack of oversized panda bears piled on top of each other against a black background. The pandas are rendered in gritty black and white with exaggerated features — bloodshot pink eyes, bared fangs, and massive claws. Some snarl at the viewer while others sleep with one eye cracked open. Bright green bamboo leaves poke through the tangle of fur and limbs. The scale is enormous — each panda is taller than a parked truck.',img:'images/murals/2021/woes-martin.jpeg',from:'Los Angeles, CA'},
  {id:33,a:'Ya La\'Ford',t:'',loc:'255 Beach Dr NE',bldg:'Smith & Associates',lat:27.77573,lng:-82.632255,y:2021,cat:'shine',ig:'yalaford',bio:'Ya La\'Ford is a Florida-based multidisciplinary artist whose geometric murals and installations explore cultural heritage and collective memory. Her vibrant, pattern-heavy work has landed commissions with Nike, the NBA, and a project honoring Maya Angelou, and she maintains an active mural map documenting her public pieces across the state. Her SHINE 2021 mural on the Smith & Associates building along Beach Drive features a glowing orange heart rendered in warm gradients with radiating lines, turning the real estate office facade into one of the more eye-catching walls on the downtown waterfront strip.',desc:'A large orange heart dominates the wall of the Smith & Associates building, rendered in warm gradients with radiating lines that give it a glowing, luminous quality. The heart shape is built from layered brushwork, creating a textured surface that reads differently up close versus from across Beach Drive.',img:'images/murals/2024/ya-la-ford.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:98,a:'Brian Butler',t:'',loc:'1101 1st Ave N',bldg:'MUV Dispensary',lat:27.77247,lng:-82.65004667,y:2020,cat:'shine',ig:'upperhandart',bio:'Brian Butler runs Upper Hand Art out of Miami, working across murals, illustration, gigposters, and live concert drawing. His "Show Drawn" series documents over 2,000 live performances sketched on-site at venues across the country. He\'s done album art for GZA, murals for Target and LAFC, and painted at POW!WOW! festivals in Worcester and Hawaii. His 2020 SHINE mural wraps the MUV Dispensary building in a sprawling nature scene — dense vegetation, birds, and flowing organic linework that turns the commercial facade into something closer to a botanical garden wall. The bold outlines and hand-illustrated feel are distinctly Butler.',desc:'A large-scale nature scene wraps the MUV Dispensary building, featuring dense tropical foliage, birds in flight, and flowing organic linework. The composition covers multiple faces of the building, creating an immersive green canopy effect. Bold outlines define the plant forms while softer color fills give the whole piece a hand-illustrated, almost storybook quality.',img:'images/murals/2020/brian-butler.jpeg',from:'Miami, Florida'},
  {id:117,a:'Palehorse',t:'Saraswati Goddess',loc:'',bldg:'',lat:27.77232167,lng:-82.64343333,y:2020,cat:'commercial',ig:'palehorsedesign',bio:'Palehorse (Chris Parks) is a St. Petersburg-based illustrator and fine artist who co-founded and curated the SHINE Mural Festival from 2015 to 2017. His highly detailed work draws on Southeast Asian and Latin mythology, and he\'s landed commercial projects with Nike, Under Armour, National Geographic, Hasbro, DC Comics, WWE, Red Bull, and Harley-Davidson. He\'s exhibited at Art Basel Miami and in galleries in LA, New York, Berlin, and Jakarta. The Saraswati Goddess mural, painted in August 2020 with his brother Matthew Parks and Cat Gomez, fills a building wall with an intricate depiction of the Hindu goddess of knowledge and arts. Saraswati plays a veena flanked by a swan and peacock, with an Om symbol and Devanagari script, all rendered in meticulous white and gold linework on a deep black background.',desc:'A massive black-and-gold mural depicting Saraswati, the Hindu goddess of knowledge and the arts. The multi-armed figure plays a veena (stringed instrument) at center, surrounded by extraordinary ornamental detail — a swan on the left, a peacock on the right, an Om symbol above, and the word "सरस्वती" (Saraswati) in Devanagari script. The entire composition is rendered in white and gold linework on a jet-black background, giving it the quality of an illuminated manuscript at building scale.',img:'images/murals/2020/palehorse.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:113,a:'Morning Breath',t:'',loc:'250 Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. St N',bldg:'Coney Island Sandwich Shop',lat:27.774544,lng:-82.647133,y:2019,cat:'shine',ig:'morningbreathinc',bio:'Morning Breath Inc. is the creative duo of Doug Cunningham and Jason Noto, who met in 1996 while working at Think Skateboards in San Francisco. They founded their boutique design studio in 2002, now based in Brooklyn. Their style draws heavily from 1950s–1980s Americana — comics, Mad magazine, punk rock, hip-hop, heavy metal, and skateboarding. They use limited color palettes, bold lines, and vintage pop culture elements. Clients include Ray-Ban, Nike, Adidas, Vans, Beats by Dre, Jay-Z, and Foo Fighters. They have designed packaging for over 100 albums and won a Grammy Award in 2021 for Best Recording Package for Desert Sessions Volumes 11 & 12. They also painted a SHINE mural in 2015 at 2042 Central Avenue (since lost to development).',desc:'A 101-by-15-foot brush-painted mural in black, white, and red on a pale blue background, designed to look like a vintage comic book pamphlet held open wide. At left, the Steeplechase "Funny Face" from Coney Island grins with a missing tooth. The center features a sinister figure in a red jacket holding a "Welcome to Fear City" pamphlet — a reference to the real 1975 New York City scare pamphlet. Phrases like "GHASTLY," "STARTLING SECRETS of Mystery," "JITTERY NERVES," and "Picture You NERVOUS" are scattered across the composition in retro horror-comic typography. At far right, a large red devil face with curling mustache and horns looms above the wall. The mural was inspired by the Coney Island Sandwich Shop (operating since 1926) and contains subtle nods to New York City throughout.',img:'images/murals/2019/morning-breath.jpeg',from:'Brooklyn, NY'},
  {id:115,a:'Derek Donnelly',t:'365 Million Things To Do',loc:'54 7th St N',bldg:'Morean Arts Center (east wall)',lat:27.771672,lng:-82.644081,y:2018,cat:'shine',ig:'saintpaintarts',bio:'Derek Donnelly is a St. Petersburg native who graduated from Pinellas County Center for the Arts at Gibbs High School in 2001, then studied graphic design and digital illustration at IADT Tampa. He has been a full-time muralist since 2010. In 2011 he opened Saint Paint Arts gallery on the 600 block of Central Avenue, helping launch several artists\' careers before closing in 2014 to focus on murals. He later founded COVE gallery in Pinellas Park and Public Art Project Inc., a nonprofit promoting public art. His playful, illustration- meets-realism style frequently features his son Syre and Florida wildlife. Clients include AARP, Hilton Hotels, Tampa Bay Rays, MLB, and Fender Guitars. He is a multiple Best of the Bay winner and was selected as inaugural Artmaker 2026 artist at Ruth Eckerd Hall. For SHINE 2025 he served as Operations Lead and artist liaison.',desc:'A whimsical mural on the east wall of the Morean Arts Center depicting an anthropomorphic T-Rex dinosaur wearing a brown fedora, round glasses, and a blue-and-white Hawaiian shirt, holding a fishing rod over the waterfront. A pink-and-blue sunset sky frames a distant city skyline across the bay. The mural is part of Donnelly\'s AARP "Age Friendly St. Pete" series — the T-Rex going fishing represents "the older generation of St. Pete enjoying life to the fullest." Signed "Donnelly @saintpaintarts."',img:'images/murals/2018/derek-donnelly-365-million.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:114,a:'J&S Signs',t:'Point of Pines',loc:'553 9th St N',bldg:'',lat:27.778658,lng:-82.646439,y:2018,cat:'shine',ig:'jandssigns',bio:'J&S Signs is a vintage hand-lettering collaboration between Jeffrey Sincich (b. 1990, Belleair, FL) and Josh Stover, who met as ceramics majors at the University of Florida. After graduating in 2012, they began painting positive-message murals and transitioned into professional sign painting, founding J&S Signs in 2013 in St. Petersburg. They relocated to Portland, Oregon around 2015. Their style draws from 1930s–1950s lettering — bold, simple, with distinctive letter shapes and a signature mint-and-red palette. In 2021 they rebranded as "Variety Shop." Clients include Nike, Adidas, Patagonia, Airbnb, and the Portland Trail Blazers. Other well-known St. Pete murals include "You Are My Sunshine" at the Morean Arts Center and "Love Your Neighborhood" on Central Avenue.',desc:'A 15-by-60-foot mural in a retro, bold children\'s-book style using muted pink, mustard brown, sea green, and orange. The composition depicts three vintage St. Pete buildings: a green one-story motel at left with a 1950s neon "Motel" sign and an "All Are Welcome" placard; a two-story mustard post office at center with archways and a vintage "Oranges $1.99" sign; and a pink two-story apartment at right with orange and brown columns. The title "Point of Pines" references the Spanish meaning of "Pinellas" — the county\'s original name. Period details include a green bench, palm trees, and a layered skyline evoking mid-century Florida.',img:'images/murals/2018/js-signs-point-of-pines.jpeg',from:'Portland, OR (originally St. Petersburg, FL)'},
  {id:111,a:'Sarah Sheppard',t:'Life Reimagined',loc:'719 Central Ave',bldg:'Morean Arts Center',lat:27.771703,lng:-82.644097,y:2017,cat:'shine',ig:'sarah.g.sheppard',bio:'Sarah Sheppard is an experienced painter, muralist, designer, and metalsmith based in St. Petersburg, Florida. She draws inspiration from the people and places she has encountered around the world, aiming to convey beauty, romanticism, and mysticism in every medium. She also participated in SHINE 2023 with a mural at New Dawn Coffee Co.',desc:'A mural on the back wall of the Morean Arts Center framed with a navy blue border and ornate gold trim, giving it the appearance of a steampunk painting. At center, a woman merges with a banyan tree — her body becoming the trunk, her roots spreading into the ground. She reaches out to a red phoenix bird at left, symbolizing rebirth. The right side features massive interlocking bronze and gold gears representing the passage of time and the mechanics of working life. Teal water fills the base. Commissioned by AARP as part of the "Age Friendly St. Pete" SHINE All Year program in 2017.',img:'images/murals/2017/sarah-sheppard-life-reimagined.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:108,a:'Stephen Palladino',t:'',loc:'276 Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd N',bldg:'Benson Worley Architecture',lat:27.774639,lng:-82.646994,y:2017,cat:'shine',ig:'goodandshiddy',bio:'Stephen Palladino (b. 1986, Bronx, NY) is a globally recognized artist whose style merges street culture, fine art, and raw emotional storytelling. His father was a carpenter and pinstriper, his mother brought Sicilian heritage. By age 10 his talent earned him a spot in a magnet art program for formal classical training, but his true education came painting large-scale murals throughout New York City as a teenager. He left high school to pursue painting full-time. His signature distorted characters blend graffiti, cartoons, and German Expressionism into work that is "slick and gritty, dark and lowbrow." Collaborations include Lady Gaga, Tiffany & Co., Playboy, Absolut Vodka, Reebok, American Express, Capital One, and Hilton. He won First Place in Painting at the Beverly Hills artSHOW in 2016. Also known as "Good and Shiddy."',desc:'A 17-by-95-foot mural on the south wall of Benson Worley Architecture featuring a dense composition of distorted human figures and faces in bright fluorescent colors — aqua, orange, lime green, purple, blue, and rosy red. From a distance the forms read as a cheery abstract puzzle, but up close bold black line drawings reveal Palladino\'s expressive, German Expressionism- influenced style. Characters include an orange woman, a blue-suited man, and a red woman in profile, interspersed with phrases like "LOVE ME," "AIN\'T," "NOBODY but YOU," "LOOKIN NEAT," "GAS," "YO!," and "NOT TRUE" scrawled in handwritten text across the wall.',img:'images/murals/2017/stephen-palladino.jpeg',from:'Los Angeles / New York'},
  {id:112,a:'Alex Pardee',t:'Brightmares',loc:'251 10th St N',bldg:'',lat:27.774586,lng:-82.647125,y:2016,cat:'shine',ig:'alexpardee',bio:'Alex Pardee (b. 1976, Antioch, CA) is an American freelance artist, illustrator, and comics creator. Hospitalized at 14 while struggling with depression, art became his critical outlet. He started in graffiti and homemade sketch zines before publishing his first book "My Book of Colors" in 1999. His signature aesthetic — which he calls "Brightmares" — features fantastical, dark creatures rendered in unexpectedly vibrant colors. He illustrated album art for The Used, Aesop Rock, and In Flames, and worked on creature design for films including "Attack the Block" and "Sucker Punch." He served as Art Director and Creature Designer for "Digging Up the Marrow" (2014). Collaborations include Warner Bros., KidRobot, and Teddy Fresh. He is represented by Harman Projects and Spoke Art galleries.',desc:'A 46-by-19-foot mural depicting an emaciated, skeletal gray figure hunched beneath an enormous dripping concentric-circle orb in pink, blue, green, yellow, and orange — like a deflating rainbow balloon where the figure\'s head should be. The creature has elongated bony limbs and stands on bulbous white and tan blobs that spurt upward from the ground. A swirling black vortex fills the background. Colors drip downward from the orb as if melting in the Florida heat. This was the largest mural Pardee had ever attempted at the time, completed with assistance from fellow artist Ricky Watts.',img:'images/murals/2016/alex-pardee.jpeg',from:'Los Angeles, CA'},
  {id:110,a:'Shark Toof',t:'',loc:'687 Central Ave',bldg:'State Theater',lat:27.771683,lng:-82.643142,y:2015,cat:'shine',ig:'shark__toof',bio:'Shark Toof (David Lew) is an American graffiti artist, stencillist, and muralist based in Los Angeles. He started painting graffiti in 1985 and is a graduate of ArtCenter College of Design in Pasadena. He is best known for his wheat-pasted images of a hand-drawn, gape-mouthed great white shark, which he uses as a symbol of "strength, optimism, and possibility." His work has been commissioned by Ritz Carlton, Samsung, Apple, Hurley, Burton, and Heineken.',desc:'A massive great white shark painted in dark gray and black across the east wall of the State Theater, a pink/coral building with arched windows on Central Avenue. The shark\'s head dives downward with its mouth wide open, baring rows of white teeth, positioned above a red metal-grate door. The piece was completed over four days using approximately 100 cans of aerosol paint on the 55-by-33-foot wall. The shark\'s menacing form contrasts with the ornate architectural details of the historic theater building.',img:'images/murals/2015/shark-toof.jpeg',from:'Los Angeles, CA'},
  {id:109,a:'Chad Mize',t:'Twiggy',loc:'653 Central Ave (alley)',bldg:'Behind Bluelucy Gallery',lat:27.771628,lng:-82.642617,y:0,cat:'shine-legacy',ig:'',bio:'Chad Mize is a multimedia artist often called "St. Pete\'s Godfather of Art." He founded MIZE Gallery (formerly Bluelucy Gallery) and was a member of SHINE\'s organizing committee. He has been painting Twiggy — the 1960s fashion icon — since 2003, citing her androgynous style, 60s aesthetic, and striking eyes as inspiration. This mural, painted circa 2014, is considered one of the pioneering murals that helped establish the 600 block of Central Avenue as an arts destination, predating the first SHINE festival in 2015.',desc:'A stencilled black-and-white mural of 1960s fashion icon Twiggy\'s face in the alley behind the 600 block of Central Avenue. The image references the iconic 1966 photograph by Barry Lategan, showing Twiggy\'s signature doe eyes with stars, rendered with an iridescent sheen against a faded light blue wall. The deliberately muted, pastel-hued palette contrasts with the bolder murals in the surrounding area.',img:'images/murals/pre-shine/chad-mize-twiggy.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:116,a:'Chad Mize',t:'',loc:'421 4th Ave N',bldg:'Hollander Hotel',lat:27.777111,lng:-82.638869,y:0,cat:'commercial',ig:'chadmize',bio:'Chad Mize is a multimedia artist often called "St. Pete\'s Godfather of Art." He founded MIZE Gallery (formerly Bluelucy Gallery) and was a member of SHINE\'s organizing committee. His bold, colorful illustration style draws from pop art, comics, and Florida culture. He has multiple murals across St. Petersburg including the iconic Twiggy portrait behind his former gallery on Central Avenue.',desc:'A large three-story commercial mural on the side of the Hollander Hotel in Chad Mize\'s signature bold-line illustration style. On a white background, colorful vignettes in orange, teal, yellow, and pink depict Florida icons — flamingos, a pink dolphin, an orange slice, a mermaid, a seahorse, beach chairs, palm trees, and a retro couple in swimwear splashing in the surf. "St. Pete" appears in playful lettering at top, "HH Hollander Hotel" in gold at center, and "Florida" in a retro script below. NÜTRL Vodka Seltzer branding appears in the upper right. Signed "@CHADMIZE."',img:'images/murals/commercial/chad-mize-hollander.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:119,a:'Matt Kress',t:'',loc:'1st St N & Dr. MLK Jr St N',bldg:'Animal Hospital',lat:27.77230833,lng:-82.64711167,y:0,cat:'commercial',ig:'mattkressart',bio:'Matt Kress is an Ohio native who studied art and graphic design at Kent State University, spent 16 years in business, then moved to St. Petersburg and went full-time as an artist in 2018. He\'s since painted 30-plus murals nationwide, including a piece for the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. He also created "The Mooney Anomaly," one of the world\'s first flying artworks, recognized internationally in aviation circles. His dogs-and-cats mural wraps the animal hospital at MLK and 1st Street North with a colorful, geometric pop-art treatment — a Boston terrier, a large dark dog, and a tabby cat rendered in bold color blocks against kaleidoscopic diamond patterns.',desc:'A long wall covered with oversized portraits of dogs and cats in a colorful geometric pop-art style. A Boston terrier, a large dark dog, and a tabby cat with prominent whiskers are painted in bold, faceted color blocks — blues, oranges, greens, reds — set against a kaleidoscopic background of intersecting diamond patterns. The style is vibrant and eye-catching from the parking lot.',img:'images/murals/commercial/unknown-1503.jpeg',from:'St. Petersburg, FL'},
  {id:107,a:'Melanie Posner',t:'',loc:'421 4th Ave N',bldg:'Hollander Hotel',lat:27.776736,lng:-82.638808,y:0,cat:'commercial',ig:'therealmelpoz',bio:'Melanie Posner is a fine artist and muralist from Philadelphia who earned her BFA in Painting from the University of Tampa in 2016. She specializes in vibrant, photorealistic paintings of women. Her clients include Walt Disney World (scenic artwork for Star Wars: Galaxy\'s Edge), Amazon Prime, and TikTok (a 40-foot mural on the LGBT Center of Los Angeles for Pride Month). She also has a SHINE 2018 mural "New Beginnings" at 4139 7th Terrace S. She was a cast member on the reality show Tampa Baes. Now based in Los Angeles.',desc:'An 18-foot-tall commercial mural on the back entrance of the Hollander Hotel near the swimming pool and tiki bar. A confident woman wearing a red head scarf and dark sunglasses holds a tall glass of beer, rendered in photorealistic style. The background features a bold psychedelic paisley pattern in mint green, yellow, and pink with black and white teardrop motifs. Signed "Melanie Posner" in the upper right, with "@muralcerveza" and "@therealmelpoz" at the bottom. Commissioned by New Belgium Brewing to promote their Mural Agua Fresca Cerveza summer beer.',img:'images/murals/commercial/melanie-posner-hollander.jpeg',from:'Los Angeles, CA'}
];

